Usage Guide

--

A. Lora Weight

  • 0.1 ~ 0.4 -- is to combine multiple faces or features, or if you experience overbaking

  • 0.5 ~ 0.7 -- is a balanced weight to get still accurate feature but with more flexiblity

  • 0.8 ~ 1.0 -- is to create accurate representation of the features.

B. CFG Scale

  • Lower CFG Scale means AI gets more creative and less overbaking problems.

  • Higher CFG Scale means results get very accurate with training sets and more prone to overbaking problems.

  • Dynamic CFG Threshold, using this method allows you to bump up quality and achieve photorealistic easily, but with lycoris i found out recently that this method actually lower success rate, so only use when you are composing with a Lora / model that works fine with this method.

C. Sampling Steps, High Res Fix & Upscaling

  • I like to use sampling steps at 50, with high res step at 20, or 1/2 of sampling steps.

  • I find that 2M Karras works better and faster than SDE Karras. with ERSGAN 4x+ method + ERSGAN 4x for Upscaling. This method actually gives quite good result without being too sharp or too plasticky

  • Upscaling - GPFGAN @0.25, Codeformer @0.3 & Codeformer Weight @0.15 seems to yield superior results to me.

--

Combining with Attribute LoRa / LyCoris

You may need to do your own testing, but using character weight 0.2 below attribute lora weight yields superior results, if for some reason one features persists not showing or overbake, you may want to lower the weight of the overbaked feature Lora, and then use emphasis () to boost the specific attribute you want.

DDetailer Script

If subject face is small / far away use: DDetailer Script with bbox anime face with default settings except denoiser at 0.2-0.3. You can combine this LoRa with a lot of other Style / Attire / Pose / Acts LoRa, Also works well with character LyCoris.

How to install this script? I kinda forget how because its a bit complicated beacuse you need to install stuff from venv. but a quick google search will land you somewhere in tutorial page.

Please leave a review if you have any critiques or if you find this LoRa good.

Based on 586 image dataset of specific style.

100% SFW.

Generally, this is not supposed to be used for anythin complex(prompt wise), because it was not tagged in a way to be.


GPTS Lazy Styles will have a lot of bleed and lower than average editability. Their purpose is to generally capture feel/style of specific dataset.

This time i've added a bonus processing to dataset, which tried to determine if image is simple, normal, or complex, based on heatmap of HED processing.(Bless ChatGPT4)

And yes, i skipped over GPTS9 and 10. Their datasets were of insufficient size, and are too weak to be reliably used for the styles they want to be, so, not today.

Salt. Just Salt.

Usage Guide

--

A. Lora Weight

  • 0.1 ~ 0.4 -- is to combine multiple faces or features, or if you experience overbaking

  • 0.5 ~ 0.7 -- is a balanced weight to get still accurate feature but with more flexiblity

  • 0.8 ~ 1.0 -- is to create accurate representation of the features.

B. CFG Scale

  • Lower CFG Scale means AI gets more creative and less overbaking problems.

  • Higher CFG Scale means results get very accurate with training sets and more prone to overbaking problems.

  • Dynamic CFG Threshold, using this method allows you to bump up quality and achieve photorealistic easily, but with lycoris i found out recently that this method actually lower success rate, so only use when you are composing with a Lora / model that works fine with this method.

C. Sampling Steps, High Res Fix & Upscaling

  • I like to use sampling steps at 50, with high res step at 20, or 1/2 of sampling steps.

  • I find that 2M Karras works better and faster than SDE Karras. with ERSGAN 4x+ method + ERSGAN 4x for Upscaling. This method actually gives quite good result without being too sharp or too plasticky

  • Upscaling - GPFGAN @0.25, Codeformer @0.3 & Codeformer Weight @0.15 seems to yield superior results to me.

--

Combining with Attribute LoRa / LyCoris

You may need to do your own testing, but using character weight 0.2 below attribute lora weight yields superior results, if for some reason one features persists not showing or overbake, you may want to lower the weight of the overbaked feature Lora, and then use emphasis () to boost the specific attribute you want.

DDetailer Script

If subject face is small / far away use: DDetailer Script with bbox anime face with default settings except denoiser at 0.2-0.3. You can combine this LoRa with a lot of other Style / Attire / Pose / Acts LoRa, Also works well with character LyCoris.

How to install this script? I kinda forget how because its a bit complicated beacuse you need to install stuff from venv. but a quick google search will land you somewhere in tutorial page.

Please leave a review if you have any critiques or if you find this LoRa good.

Usage Guide

--

A. Lora Weight

  • 0.1 ~ 0.4 -- is to combine multiple faces or features, or if you experience overbaking

  • 0.5 ~ 0.7 -- is a balanced weight to get still accurate feature but with more flexiblity

  • 0.8 ~ 1.0 -- is to create accurate representation of the features.

B. CFG Scale

  • Lower CFG Scale means AI gets more creative and less overbaking problems.

  • Higher CFG Scale means results get very accurate with training sets and more prone to overbaking problems.

  • Dynamic CFG Threshold, using this method allows you to bump up quality and achieve photorealistic easily, but with lycoris i found out recently that this method actually lower success rate, so only use when you are composing with a Lora / model that works fine with this method.

C. Sampling Steps, High Res Fix & Upscaling

  • I like to use sampling steps at 50, with high res step at 20, or 1/2 of sampling steps.

  • I find that 2M Karras works better and faster than SDE Karras. with ERSGAN 4x+ method + ERSGAN 4x for Upscaling. This method actually gives quite good result without being too sharp or too plasticky

  • Upscaling - GPFGAN @0.25, Codeformer @0.3 & Codeformer Weight @0.15 seems to yield superior results to me.

--

Combining with Attribute LoRa / LyCoris

You may need to do your own testing, but using character weight 0.2 below attribute lora weight yields superior results, if for some reason one features persists not showing or overbake, you may want to lower the weight of the overbaked feature Lora, and then use emphasis () to boost the specific attribute you want.

DDetailer Script

If subject face is small / far away use: DDetailer Script with bbox anime face with default settings except denoiser at 0.2-0.3. You can combine this LoRa with a lot of other Style / Attire / Pose / Acts LoRa, Also works well with character LyCoris.

How to install this script? I kinda forget how because its a bit complicated beacuse you need to install stuff from venv. but a quick google search will land you somewhere in tutorial page.

Please leave a review if you have any critiques or if you find this LoRa good.

Eye Direction

Ñ„Ğ°Ğ¹Ğ» Ğ½Ğ° civitaiÑÑ‚Ñ€Ğ°Ğ½Ğ¸Ñ†Ğ° Ğ½Ğ° civitai

About this Model

This LyCORIS:Locon model, eyedirectionV1.6, is for orienting the direction of the eye without using the popular keywords "looking away" in the positive prompt. The model changes eye direction while minimizing large head turns. ("looking away" is not bad if we want significant head turns, but for subtle turns it is too much for some of our setups.

How to Apply

Trigger: eyedirection

Settings:

Weight: 0.3 - 0.5

Methods: DPM++ 2M/2Sa/SDE Karras

Steps: 25 - 30

CFG: 7-14

Positive prompt keyword options:

eyes up, eyes down, eyes up left, eyes up right, eyes down left, eyes down right, eyes left, eyes right, looking above, looking below, looking sideways, eyes left looking sideways, eyes right looking sideways, eyes up looking above, eyes down looking below, eyes up right looking above, eyes down right looking below, eyes up left looking above, eyes down left looking below

ex. <lyco:eyedirectionV1.6:0.3> eyedirection, eyes left looking sideways, (solo, portrait:1.4)

For random eye direction, at least the word "eyes" must be present in the prompt:

ex. <lyco:eyedirectionV1.6:0.3> eyedirection, brown eyes, (solo, portrait:1.4)

Negative prompt:

(eye contact, eye to eye, looking at viewer, looks at viewer:1.5)

Limitations

It will work in models with realistic or photorealism in them. I have not directly tried it with anime models, and since this is my very Very VERY first model, there are still room for improvements and upgrades, so expect for next versions. Also, use this model responsibly and within legalities.
